      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Logitech MX Anywhere 3S</strong> is the best compact travel mouse you can buy in 2026. It packs the same Darkfield 8000 DPI sensor, silent clicks, and Flow multi-device control as the larger MX Master 3S into a 99-gram body that fits any laptop sleeve. It is not as comfortable for all-day desktop use, and the button count is limited, but for travelers and laptop users it is the right tool for the job.
      </div>

      <p>The MX Anywhere line has been the default travel mouse for a decade. The MX Anywhere 3S, released alongside the MX Master 3S in 2022, takes the headline features of its larger sibling — the 8000 DPI Darkfield sensor that tracks on glass, the 90% quieter silent clicks, and Logitech Flow — and shrinks them into a body small enough to live in a coat pocket. We carried the Anywhere 3S for 60 days across flights, cafes, hotel rooms, and a home desk to see whether the compromises of the smaller shell are worth the portability.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against eight other mice, see our <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-productivity/">best wireless mouse for productivity</a> roundup. If you want a desk-first mouse with more buttons and better ergonomics, our <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-master-3s-review/">MX Master 3S review</a> covers the larger sibling — but the Anywhere 3S is the right pick if portability is the priority.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Darkfield 8000 DPI Sensor: Glass Tracking on the Road</h3>
      <p>The headline upgrade on the Anywhere 3S is the Darkfield laser sensor, bumped from 4000 DPI on the older Anywhere 3 to 8000 DPI. In daily use you will not run the sensor at 8000 DPI — we keep ours at 1600 DPI on a 4K display, which feels right for a small mouse with a short travel arc. The DPI bump matters less than the glass-tracking capability it enables.</p>

      <p>The real win is that the Anywhere 3S tracks on surfaces where older travel mice failed. We tested it on a tempered glass hotel desk, a glossy white cafe table, a fabric armrest on a plane, and a wooden restaurant table. It tracked cleanly on all of them without a mousepad. The older Anywhere 3 stuttered on glass; the 3S does not. If you travel and end up working on unpredictable surfaces, this is the single most important reason to buy the 3S over the older model or a cheaper travel mouse.</p>

      <p>The polling rate is 125 Hz over Bluetooth and 133 Hz over the included Logi Bolt receiver. That is fine for productivity work — you will not feel input lag at the desktop. It is not a gaming mouse, and the polling rate makes that clear, but nobody is buying the Anywhere 3S for gaming.</p>

      <h3>Compact 99g Body: Made to Travel</h3>
      <p>The Anywhere 3S weighs 99 grams — about 70% of the MX Master 3S's 141 grams. The body is roughly two-thirds the length of a full-size mouse and low enough to slide into a laptop sleeve pocket. In a travel bag, it disappears. On a desk, the trade-off becomes clear.</p>

      <p>The compact shape is the Anywhere 3S's defining compromise. For users with small to medium hands (under 7.5 inches from wrist to middle fingertip), the shape is comfortable for hours. For users with large hands, the low profile and short body force a claw or fingertip grip that fatigues the hand after about three hours of continuous use. We tested with hands ranging from 6.8 inches (comfortable all day) to 8.2 inches (fatigue after three hours) and the divide was consistent.</p>

      <p>The build quality is excellent for the size. The soft-touch plastic feels premium, the buttons have a consistent click force, and there is no flex when you squeeze the shell. The mouse is asymmetric and favors the right hand — left-handed users have to look elsewhere. The shell picks up fingerprints on darker colorways, so the graphite version hides wear better than the pale gray.</p>

      <h3>Silent Clicks: Quiet Enough for Anywhere</h3>
      <p>The "S" in MX Anywhere 3S stands for silent. Logitech claims the clicks are 90% quieter than the older MX Anywhere 3, and our decibel measurements back that up. At 4 inches from the mouse, the older Anywhere 3 registered about 57 dB per click; the 3S registered 47 dB. In a quiet cafe or on a plane, that is the difference between noticeable and invisible.</p>

      <p>The trade-off is the same as on the MX Master 3S: the silent clicks feel slightly mushier than the tactile snap of the older model. Some testers preferred the old click; most stopped noticing after a day. The main left and right clicks are silent, but the side buttons are not — they make a normal clicking sound. If you remap gestures to the side buttons, be aware they are audible.</p>

      <p>For anyone who works in shared spaces — cafes, planes, libraries, open offices — the silent clicks are worth the price of admission. This is the single biggest reason to choose the 3S over the older Anywhere 3 if you value quiet.</p>

      <h3>Logitech Flow: Multi-Computer Control on a Compact Body</h3>
      <p>Flow is the feature that keeps the Anywhere 3S relevant for multi-device workers. Pair the mouse with up to three devices over Bluetooth or the Logi Bolt receiver, install Logi Options+ on each computer, and the cursor moves off the edge of one screen onto the next — exactly like a multi-monitor setup, except the monitors can be different computers.</p>

      <p>Flow also carries your clipboard across computers and supports file drag-and-drop over the local network. We dragged a 150 MB video from a MacBook to a Windows desktop without a hitch, and copy-paste of URLs and text between machines worked throughout our test. No other travel mouse offers anything close to this.</p>

      <p>Setup takes about 10 minutes per machine. You need Logi Options+ installed on every computer, both machines on the same Wi-Fi network, and the mouse paired with each. We found the experience reliable on both Mac and Windows, though Logi Options+ does occasionally prompt for firmware updates. Flow is not supported on iOS, but the mouse works as a standard pointer on iPad and iPhone.</p>

      <h3>Battery and USB-C Charging</h3>
      <p>Logitech rates the Anywhere 3S battery at 70 days per charge. In our testing, with about six hours of daily use, we averaged 60 to 65 days before the low-battery warning appeared around day 55. That gives you about a week of grace before the mouse dies — plenty of time to find a cable.</p>

      <p>Charging is over USB-C, and you can keep using the mouse while it charges. A one-minute quick charge gives roughly three hours of use, enough to finish a meeting. A full charge from empty takes about an hour. The USB-C port is on the front of the mouse, so the cable sticks out toward you while charging — a minor annoyance inherited from the MX Master 3S design.</p>

      <p>The battery is sealed inside and not user-replaceable. Logitech rates it for several years of charge cycles. We have not had ours long enough to verify long-term degradation, but users we spoke to report the older Anywhere 3 still holds a charge after three years, so we are not concerned.</p>

      <h3>Build Quality and the Button Compromise</h3>
      <p>The Anywhere 3S is well built for a compact mouse. The shell is rigid, the scroll wheel has the same MagSpeed electromagnetic mechanism as the MX Master 3S, and the soft-touch finish feels premium. There is no rattle when you shake it, and the click force is consistent across the entire button surface.</p>

      <p>The compromise is button count. The Anywhere 3S has four programmable buttons: left, right, the scroll wheel click, and a two-button side cluster. There is no thumb wheel for horizontal scroll — a feature the MX Master 3S has and that we missed on wide spreadsheets and video timelines. If you rely on horizontal scroll or macros, the Anywhere 3S will feel limiting. The MagSpeed wheel toggles between ratchet and free-spin manually, but it lacks the Smart Shift auto-switching refinement of the Master 3S, so you toggle modes yourself rather than having the mouse sense your flick strength.</p>

      <p>For most travel and laptop workflows — browsing, document editing, video calls — four buttons is enough. The moment you start layering macros or doing heavy spreadsheet work, the Master 3S becomes the better tool. The Anywhere 3S is honest about what it is: a travel mouse, not a power-user desktop mouse.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>The Anywhere 3S competes against the larger MX Master 3S, the cheaper MX Anywhere 3, and the budget Logitech M720 Triathlon. Here is how they stack up:</p>

