      </table>

      <p>The <strong>MX Master 3S</strong> is the Anywhere 3S's larger sibling — same sensor, same silent clicks, same Flow, but in a body with a thumb wheel, more buttons, and better ergonomics. If you do not travel and your hands are medium-to-large, the Master 3S is the more comfortable mouse. See our <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-master-3s-review/">MX Master 3S review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>MX Anywhere 3</strong> (without the S) is the previous generation. It has the same shape and weight but lacks silent clicks and glass tracking. It frequently goes on sale for $49 to $59. If you always use a desk pad and do not need quiet clicks, it is a real bargain — but for most travelers the 3S's upgrades are worth the $20 premium.</p>

      <p>The <strong>M720 Triathlon</strong> is the budget champion at $40. It has a hyper-fast scroll wheel (mechanical, not MagSpeed), three-device pairing, and a comfortable shape. It is heavier, the sensor is weaker, and it cannot track on glass. For the price it is remarkable, but it is not a true travel mouse the way the Anywhere 3S is.</p>

      <p>Pair the Anywhere 3S with the <a href="/reviews/keychron-k8-review/">Keychron K8</a> for a travel-friendly keyboard-and-mouse combo, or check our <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-productivity/">productivity mouse roundup</a> for non-Logitech alternatives.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the MX Anywhere 3S at full price if you travel regularly, work on unpredictable surfaces, or have small to medium hands and want a compact mouse for a laptop. The combination of glass tracking, silent clicks, and Flow in a 99-gram body is unmatched at this price.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Logitech runs promotions around Prime Day and Black Friday where the MX Anywhere 3S drops to $59 to $69. We have seen it as low as $49 during clearance events. Set a price alert if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Skip the older MX Anywhere 3 unless it is heavily discounted. The older version lacks silent clicks and struggles on glass — two of the three reasons to buy the Anywhere line in the first place. Paying $20 less for a meaningfully worse sensor and louder clicks is not a good deal unless you always carry a mousepad.</p>

      <p>If you do not travel, get the <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-master-3s-review/">MX Master 3S</a> instead. It costs $20 more, but the larger body, thumb wheel, and extra buttons make it a better daily driver for a desk. The Anywhere 3S is the right mouse when portability is the priority — and the wrong mouse when it is not.</p>

      <p>Avoid no-name travel mice on Amazon. Several look identical to the Anywhere 3S at a quarter of the price, but the sensors skip on glass, the scroll wheels jam, and the batteries degrade within months. Stick with Logitech, Microsoft, or Razer.</p>

